'''''Raid Over Moscow''''' ('''''Raid''''' in some countries and on reissue) is a [[video game]] by [[Access Software]] published in Europe by [[U.S. Gold]] for the [[Commodore 64]] in 1984<ref>GamesDBase - [http://gamesdbase.com/game/commodore-64/raid-over-moscow.aspx Raid Over Moscow (Commodore 64 edition)]</ref> and other microcomputers in 1985-1986.

Released during the [[Cold War]] era, ''Raid Over Moscow'' is an [[action game]] in which the player (an American [[Astronaut ranks and positions|space pilot]]) has to stop three [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[nuclear attack]]s on [[North America]], then fight his way into and destroy a nuclear facility located in [[Moscow]]'s [[Kremlin]]. According to the game's storyline, the United States is unable to respond to the attack directly due to the [[SALT|dismantlement of its nuclear arsenal]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.worldofspectrum.org/showmag.cgi?mag=C+VG/Issue038/Pages/CVG03800076.jpg | journal = Computer and Video Games | title = Raid over Moscow <nowiki>[advertisement]</nowiki> | issue = 38 | page = 76 |date=December 1984 }}</ref>

The game is famous in [[Finland]] due to the political effect of its content. A [[Left-wing politics|leftist]] member of the [[Finnish parliament]] went as far as to make a parliamentary question about whether it was acceptable to sell the game.<ref name="iltalehti">{{cite journal | journal = Iltalehti | date = 22 February 1985 | title = Hyökkäys Moskovaan. Videopeli kauhistutti kansanedustajan }}</ref><ref name="printti">{{cite journal | journal = Printti | issue = 5 | year = 1985 | title = Mikropelit nousivat päivänpolitiikkaan }}</ref> The resulting debate and publicity made the game a top seller in the country.<ref name="topseller">{{cite web | url = http://www.widerscreen.fi/1999-1-2/tietokonepelit-osana-audiovisuaalisen-kulttuurin-moraalipaniikkia/ | first = Petri | last = Saarikoski | work = Wider Screen | issue = 1–2 | year = 1999 | title = Tietokonepelit osana audiovisuaalisen kulttuurin moraalipaniikkia | language = Finnish | access-date = 3 September 2012 | archive-date = 2021-02-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210225133859/http://www.widerscreen.fi/1999-1-2/tietokonepelit-osana-audiovisuaalisen-kulttuurin-moraalipaniikkia/ | url-status = dead }}</ref>

== Gameplay ==

=== First stage ===
[[File:raid over moscow C64.png|left|thumb|Screen shot from the [[Commodore 64]] version showing early gameplay]]
The game opens with an alert that a [[nuclear missile]] has been launched from a Soviet city towards a North American city.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=3}}<ref name="manual">{{cite web | url = ftp://ftp.worldofspectrum.org/pub/sinclair/games-info/r/RaidOverMoscow.txt | title = Raid over Moscow, instructions | first1 = Brian | last1 = Hendricks | first2 = Magnus | last2 = Welander | first3 = Alessandro | last3 = Grussu | access-date = 17 March 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The game begins in the hangar where the American [[spaceplane]]s are stored. The player has to safely fly the craft out.<ref name="manual" /> The view switches to the earth as seen from [[low Earth orbit]], and the player guides the spaceplane to the city launching the attack. Alternatively, the player may decide to maneuver more of the available spaceplanes out of the space station before attacking the launch site;{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=3}} the surplus planes are docked outside the space station.<ref name="manual" /> Meanwhile, the clock is ticking, and the time before impact is continually displayed.

[[File:Raid_over_Moscow_Atari_8-bit_PAL_screenshot.png|thumb|right|First stage gameplay (Atari 8-bit)]]
The player has then to fly through the defense perimeter around the launch site [[missile silo]], dodging obstacles, [[heat-seeking missile]]s, and Soviet tanks and planes.<ref name="manual" /> If successful, the player proceeds to the next screen; otherwise, the player has to start the next [[life (gaming)|life]] back at the hangar, with the clock still ticking. However, should the player have spare spaceplanes parked outside the space station, the game continues with a new life on the current screen, skipping the flight from space station to the launch site. The decision to launch more than a single spaceplane first may therefore save time if the player later loses a life.<ref name="manual" />

The final part of this stage involves destroying the missile silo while avoiding Soviet planes trying to shoot down the player. Destroying the primary missile silo in the center before the missile lands will thwart the attack. Destroying the secondary silos on either side of the primary earns extra lives and points.<ref name="manual" />

The Soviets launched a total of four missile attacks, from [[Leningrad]], [[Kiev]], [[Minsk]], and [[Saratov]], all of which must be stopped in the same manner as the first. After the fourth launch, the player progresses to the second stage of the game.<ref name="manual" />

=== Second stage ===
[[File:Moscow - Moscow State Historical Museum (Red Square).jpg|thumbnail|right|The [[State Historical Museum]] is used as a backdrop in the second stage of the game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mobygames.com/game/c64/raid-over-moscow/screenshots/gameShotId,320496/ | title = Screenshot: Fighting in Moscow | date = 24 August 2008 | first = Simon | last = Stelling | access-date = 16 March 2013 | work = MobyGames }}</ref>]]
The pilots become [[foot soldier]]s and are placed [[Red Square|outside the front facade]] of the "Defence Centre", depicted as the [[State Historical Museum]]. Using a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] they must blast open the correct door to the facility, randomly chosen from five available. Bonus points can be gained from this section by destroying parts of the building and defeating the troops stationed there. Once the door is open, the soldiers make their way to the [[nuclear reactor]], and the final stage of the game.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=3}}<ref name="manual" />

=== Third stage ===
In this stage, the player has to destroy maintenance [[robot]]s that feed coolant into the reactor. The number of robots is determined by the difficulty level chosen by the player. The player is provided with several disc grenades that he throws at the robot, which is moving and firing at him the entire time. The robot is reinforced at the front, so the only way to do any damage is to bounce the discs off the wall and hit the robot in the back. As the number of discs is limited, the player should attempt to catch returning discs that missed the robot. To complete the game, all robots must be defeated, the final one within a two-minute time limit. If the robot is not destroyed within the limit the game is still considered complete, but with no survivors.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=3}}<ref name="manual" />

== Releases ==
The game was first published for the  [[Commodore 64]] with [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[BBC Micro]], and [[ZX Spectrum]] versions following.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mobygames.com/game/raid-over-moscow/credits | title = Raid over Moscow | work = MobyGames | access-date = 16 March 2013 }}</ref>  Upon reissue the game was retitled to '''''Raid'''''.

An [[Amiga]] port was in development in the late 1980s but was canceled along with [[Beach Head (video game)|Beach Head]] and [[Beach Head II: The Dictator Strikes Back]] when the developers were unable to secure a deal with the publisher, U.S. Gold.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abime.net/games/view/game/id/5879 | title = Raid over Moscow | work = Amiga Lore | access-date = 16 March 2013 }}</ref> According to the graphical artist Adrian Cummings, the graphics were at that point "99.9% complete". However, the coding was barely started.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abime.net/interviews/view/interview/id/24 | title = Adrian Robert Cummings | work = Amiga Lore | access-date = 16 March 2013 }}</ref> An Amiga port was finally released in 2020 by Reimagine Games, with programming by Erik Hogan who started from scratch to create this new conversion.

The Commodore Plus/4 received a conversion of the game in 2022.

''Raid Over Moscow'' and ''Beach-Head'' were major inspirations for the [[Commodore 64]] game Terrestrial to be published in 2023. The hangar, satellite map, shield generator, and reactor battle sequences of Terrestrial were directly inspired by Raid Over Moscow.

==Reception==
{{Video game reviews
