''Raid over Moscow'' was Access' second best-selling Commodore game as of late 1987, after ''Beach-Head''.<ref name="ferrell198712">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1987-12-computegazette/Compute_Gazette_Issue_54_1987_Dec#page/n17/mode/2up | title=The Commodore Games That Live On And On | work=Compute's Gazette | date=December 1987| access-date=24 January 2015 | author=Ferrell, Keith | pages=18–22}}</ref> The game received generally positive reviews. [[Computer and Video Games]] praised the graphics and sound of the Commodore 64 version,<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.worldofspectrum.org/showmag.cgi?mag=C+VG/Issue038/Pages/CVG03800043.jpg | journal = Computer and Video Games | title = Software reviews: <nowiki>[Raid over]</nowiki> Moscow | issue = 38 | page = 43 |date=December 1984 }}</ref> while [[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] gave the ZX Spectrum version an overall score of 92%.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.crashonline.org.uk/15/rmoscow.htm | journal = Crash | title = Raid over Moscow | issue = 15 |date=April 1985 | pages = 114–116}}</ref> The theme of the game, [[nuclear war]], was subject to questioning, however, with Computer and Video Games publishing several letters from readers arguing for and against its publication.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.worldofspectrum.org/showmag.cgi?mag=C+VG/Issue040/Pages/CVG04000005.jpg | journal = Computer and Video Games | title = Mailbag | issue = 40 | page = 5 |date=February 1985 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.worldofspectrum.org/showmag.cgi?mag=C+VG/Issue041/Pages/CVG04100007.jpg | journal = Computer and Video Games | title = Mailbag | issue = 41 | page = 7 |date=March 1985 }}</ref>

Unauthorized copies of ''Raid on Moscow'' circulated widely in East Germany during the 1980s, despite the [[Stasi]] describing it as among those games having "a particularly militaristic and inhumane nature". The West German [[Federal Department for Media Harmful to Young Persons]] added the game to its index in 1985, stating that "In older adolescents, playing (...) can lead to physical tension, anger, aggressiveness, agitated thinking, difficulty concentrating, headaches, etc." The ban automatically ended in 2010.<ref name="gießler20181121">{{Cite news |url=https://www.zeit.de/digital/games/2018-11/computer-games-gdr-stasi-surveillance-gamer-crowd/komplettansicht |title=Video Games In East Germany: The Stasi Played Along |last=Gießler |first=Denis |date=2018-11-21 |work=Die Zeit |access-date=2018-11-30 |language=de}}</ref>

=== Political crisis in Finland ===
The game was shortly presented in [[YLE]]'s current affairs television program ''A-studio'' on 13 February 1985 after being reviewed by the computer magazine ''[[MikroBitti]]''.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=4}}<ref name="astudio">{{cite web | url = http://yle.fi/elavaarkisto/artikkelit/raid_over_moscow_-peli_sai_suomessa_aikaan_poliittisen_kriisin_77485.html#media=77486 | title = Raid over Moscow -peli sai Suomessa aikaan poliittisen kriisin | work = YLE | date = 13 February 1985 | access-date = 16 March 2013 | language = Finnish }}</ref> On 20 February 1985 the leftist newspaper ''[[Tiedonantaja]]'' published an article which criticized the review and called a ban on all similar "anti-USSR" games.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=4}} Parliament member [[Ensio Laine]] ([[Finnish People's Democratic League|SKDL]]) left a parliamentary question for the [[Finnish government]] on the next day.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=4}}<ref name="kk40-1985">{{cite web | title = Kirjallinen kysymys: Amerikkalaisten CBM-pelien maahantuonnista. | url = http://www.eduskunta.fi/valtiopaivaasiat/KK+40/1985 | id = KK 40/1985 vp | publisher = Finnish parliament | language = Finnish | access-date = 16 March 2013 | date = 9 March 2007 }}</ref>

[[File:Russian embassy Helsinki.JPG|thumbnail|right|The [[Soviet embassy]] at Tehtaankatu, [[Helsinki]] was the scene of the discussions concerning the game.]]
The following days included various discussions between the Finnish foreign ministry and Soviet Union representatives.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|pp=4–6}}<ref name="mtv3-2010-01-07">{{cite web | url = http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2010/01/1028902 | title = UM/SALAISET 1985: Neuvostoliitto piti tietokonepeliä räikeänä provokaationa | first = Jarkko | last = Sipilä | work = MTV3 | date = 7 January 2010 | access-date = 16 March 2013 | language = Finnish }}</ref> On 7 March 1985, an unofficial petition was received from the USSR, asking for a ban on various books, articles and other media, including ''Raid Over Moscow'', which were supposed to purport a distorted view on the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=6}} Nevertheless, on 14 March 1985, the Minister of foreign trade [[Jermu Laine]] answered the parliamentary question, claiming that the Finnish legislation only allowed to restrict the import of products that constitute a hazard on health.<ref name="kk40-1985" />{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=6}} The foreign ministry thus was able to dodge possible claims of [[Finlandization]] by referring to unsuitable legislation.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=8}} Finally, the Minister of foreign affairs [[Paavo Väyrynen]] gave an official answer to the petition on 11 April 1985, expressing a friendly attitude towards the USSR and apologizing on behalf of negative publications about the country in the media.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|pp=6–7}} The USSR interpreted the game as military propaganda, but settled on the answer.{{sfn|Pasanen|2011|p=7}}

As a result of the public debate, the game was the top-selling Commodore 64 game in Finland from March to September 1985 according to ''MikroBitti''.<ref name="topseller"/> The full extent of the affair was unveiled in 2010, when the Finnish foreign ministry memos were declassified.<ref name="mtv3-2010-01-07" />

